Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
This EDA is based on the TikTok 2025 Dataset stored in our project directory.
Here, I explore the structure of the data, missingness patterns, distributions, and early relationships between engagement metrics like views, likes, comments, and shares.
Code

library(DataExplorer)
library(janitor)
library(visdat)
library(lubridate)

My first impression is that the dataset is fairly large and contains a mix of numeric and character variables. Seeing everything summarized like this helped me understand how the data is organized and what I will need to clean later. The dataset includes numeric engagement metrics (likes, comments, shares, plays, views) and text-based variables (description, hashtags, music, author). It also contains time variables such as create_time and posted_time, which will help explore temporal trends.

title: Raouda Mamane BelLo boubacar
text:
2. Missing Data
I started by checking where the dataset has missing values.


Code
vis_dat(df)









Code
plot_missing(df)









Reflection: The missing data visualization made it clear which variables might cause problems later. Some engagement columns (Some variables like fetch_time, posted_time have missing values) have gaps, which is not surprising since not every video might have all metrics available. Engagement metrics look mostly complete, which is good for modeling. Understanding what is missing early helps avoid problems later in the project.

Exploring Numeric Variables I wanted to understand how the numeric variables behave, especially engagement metrics.

Reflection: Looking at the top categories helped me see which creators or hashtags appear the most. A few authors seem very active, which might influence trends in the dataset. This gave me a better idea of how concentrated the dataset is around certain users.

Correlations Between Variables



Code
plot_correlation(numeric_df)









Reflection: Engagement variables (views, likes, shares, comments) seem highly correlated. This makes sense because videos that get a lot of views tend to get attention in other metrics. It also made me think about whether we need all of them later, or if some are redundant.

Correlations Between Numeric Variables Writing



Code
plot_correlation(numeric_df)









Reflection: The strongest correlations appear between views, plays, likes, and shares, which makes sense: videos with high view counts often get high engagement in other categories.

Relationships Between Key Metrics Here I looked at how views relate to likes, since this is usually the clearest pattern in social media engagement. (Replace variable names once you confirm the dataset‚Äôs actual column names.)



Code
df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = views, y = likes)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10") +
  scale_y_continuous(trans = "log10") +
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Views and Likes",
       x = "Views (log scale)",
       y = "Likes (log scale)")









Reflection: Plotting on a log scale made the pattern much clearer. There is a strong positive relationship, but the spread is pretty wide. This suggests that some videos get a lot of attention but not necessarily a proportionate number of likes. It made me think about the role of content type or timing, which might explain these differences.

Time-Based Patterns (If Time Column Exists) If the dataset contains a posting timestamp such as create_time or posted_at, this code will work:



Code
if ("create_time" %in% names(df)) {
  df %>% 
    mutate(hour_posted = hour(create_time)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(hour_posted)) +
    geom_bar() +
    labs(title = "Distribution of Posts by Hour of Day",
         x = "Hour of Day",
         y = "Number of Posts")
}









Reflection: Time-of-day patterns can be useful because engagement often depends on when the content is posted. Even if the plot is uneven, it‚Äôs useful for forming early hypotheses about user behavior.

Main Takeaways From My EDA Here are the key things I learned:


Engagement variables (views, plays, likes) are heavily skewed, with many low-engagement videos and a few very viral ones
Several creators appear often, meaning activity is not evenly distributed
Missingness mainly affects time-related fields like fetch_time and posted_time
Engagement metrics are strongly correlated with each other
Posting time varies widely, which may influence engagement trends

The relationship between views and likes is strong but not perfect, suggesting other factors matter.

title: Appendix A ‚Äî Project Proposal
text:
Project Title : TikTok Video Popularity Analysis : What Makes Tiktok Videos Go Viral ?
Team Name :  Tiktok Police Team Members :  Isa Chen, Shurui Zhang, Raouda Mamane Bello Boubacar Kinassa Category :  Entertainment

title: Appendix A ‚Äî Project Proposal
text:
Short Description of the Project
We are studying how people engage with Tiktok videos, focusing on both informational (‚Äúnews-like‚Äù) and entertainment content. We will analyze Tiktok video metadata and engagement metrics to determine which factors (hashtags, video length, creator, followers or music) influence video popularity. Our project aims to explore how trends differ between news content and entertainment content, helping us understand how social media spreads information.

title: Appendix A ‚Äî Project Proposal
text:
Research Questions
Which factors (hashtags, music, video length or followers) most strongly predict the popularity of TikTok videos? How does engagement differ between informational/news videos and entertainment videos on TikTok? What patterns in TikTok video trends can help explain how people consume news on social media platforms?

title: Appendix A ‚Äî Project Proposal
text:
Reasons and Inspiration
TikTok is one of the most influential social media for both entertainment and information sharing. While it is known for short viral content, an increasing number of users are also using TikTok for news and current events. We are interested in this topic because people of different ages use TikTok in different ways. While younger users often watch and share entertainment content, more people are also starting to get news from TikTok. By comparing how different age groups engage with news and entertainment videos, we hope to understand how TikTok influences the way people from each generation learn and share information.

title: Appendix A ‚Äî Project Proposal
text:
Dataset

Dataset Name : Tiktok Trending Videos (December 2020)

Source : Kaggle - Tiktok Trending Videos (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/erikvdven/tiktok-trending-december-2020)
Format : CSV + JSON
Size : Around 1000 trending videos



Key variables:

authorMeta.followers : Number of followers of creator
videoMeta.duration : Length of videos in seconds
text : video caption
hashtags : list of hashtags
musicMeta.musicName : Music/sound used in video
diggCount : Number of likes

shareCount : Number of shares
playCount : Number of views
commentCount : Number of comments

Notes: We will categorize videos into news (hashtags like #news, #currentevents, etc‚Ä¶.) and entertainment (all other content)

title: Appendix B ‚Äî Case Study
text:
Case Study: Dating at 50 and Up ‚Äî Older Americans‚Äô Experiences with Online Dating
Source: Pew Research Center (https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/07/17/dating-at-50-and-up-older-americans-experiences-with-online-dating/)
Team: TikTok Police
Date: October 2025

title: Appendix B ‚Äî Case Study
text:
1. Overview
This article from Pew Research Center looks at how Americans aged 50 and older use online dating and what their experiences are like. It talks about who in this age group is using dating apps, what problems they face, and how their opinions about online dating compare to younger people. The article combines simple text with a few clear charts, which makes it easy to follow.

title: Appendix B ‚Äî Case Study
text:
2. Story Structure
The story starts with a short introduction about how online dating has become more common for older adults. Then it moves into data about who is actually using dating apps and how those numbers change by gender and age.
Next, the article talks about challenges older users experience, like trouble finding matches or concerns about safety. Later sections discuss how older adults feel about dating online ‚Äî some enjoy it, but many find it frustrating or not very successful.
The story ends with a summary that connects everything back to the main point: online dating can work for older people, but it‚Äôs often a mixed experience. The flow feels natural and easy to read because every paragraph connects directly to the chart shown below it.

title: Appendix B ‚Äî Case Study
text:
3. Visual Storytelling
The visuals are simple but effective. Most of them are bar charts that show comparisons across age or gender. The color palette is clean and consistent, which helps keep the focus on the message instead of the design.
Each chart supports a single point ‚Äî for example, one shows that older women are less likely to use dating apps than men, and another shows that most people over 65 feel uncomfortable with online dating. Even though the visuals aren‚Äôt interactive, they clearly help the reader see trends in the data.

title: Appendix B ‚Äî Case Study
text:
4. Writing Style
The writing feels friendly and not too technical, which makes it easy for anyone to understand. The authors explain percentages in a casual way, like saying ‚Äúabout three in ten adults‚Äù instead of ‚Äú30%.‚Äù Each section is short and straight to the point, which makes the story flow smoothly. It also avoids complicated analysis, focusing more on describing what the data shows and why it matters.

title: Appendix B ‚Äî Case Study
text:
5. What We Learned
From this report, we learned a few things that can help with our own project.
- It‚Äôs good to focus on a clear group comparison, like how Pew compared age groups.
- The layout works well ‚Äî one idea per section with a chart to support it.
- The tone is simple and easy to read, which helps the audience stay engaged.
- The article shows how to connect data findings back to real-life experiences.
We also liked how this story focused on age differences, which is similar to our TikTok project. It reminded us that data about people should always be explained in a human way, not just shown as numbers.
